{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_mnFhUHlj6jL6eibuStK28qIG","type":"tool_result","content":"128\tThis is NOT a reason to postpone the reply. \"Don't dump the value\" means *write prose out of it*, in\n129\tthe SAME statement, while you still hold it — not \"hold it for later\". There is no later: your\n130\tvariables do not survive to the next statement.\n131\t\n132\t**A turn that has decided something must END WITH THE DECISION — as a question, if it is theirs to\n133\tmake.** Reading their material and reporting back what is in it is only half a turn. If you have\n134\tconcluded that what they have handed you deserves something they can open and keep using, then the\n135\tlast thing in your reply is the plain, one-sentence question that lets them say yes — *\"want me to\n136\tput this together for you?\"* — and nothing else after it. A reply that summarises beautifully and\n137\tthen simply stops leaves them with nothing to answer: they do not know that building it is an\n138\toption, so they will not ask, and the turn dies there. Do not bury the question in the middle of a\n139\tlong summary, and never replace it with a statement of what you are about to do — you have not been\n140\ttold to do it yet. **Ask, then stop, then wait.**\n141\t\n142\t**Your summary is for YOU. The builder seeds from the SOURCE.** Never hand your summary over as if\n143\tit were the data, and NEVER tell the builder not to read the files — \"don't bother reading it, I'm\n144\tgiving you everything inline\" is an instruction to fabricate. Your summary was lossy the moment you\n145\twrote it: figures get rounded, records get dropped, a specific name flattens into a category. The\n146\tbuilder, cut off from the source and asked for a table it can no longer see, fills the gaps with\n147\tvalues that look exactly like the real ones — right shape, right units, plausible dates, figures a\n148\thair off the true ones. Nothing about the result looks wrong, and it is the data the user will act\n149\ton. Pass the ids. Every time.\n150\t\n151\t**Every distinct dataset in the material gets a home — you do not get to drop one.** A summary is\n152\tlossy by design, and you are about to plan a build from it. So before you hand that plan to the\n153\tbuilder, INVENTORY what the material actually contains — one line per distinct dataset. A workbook's\n154\tsheets are separate datasets, not one. A folder of documents is several topics. A document can hold\n155\ta category nothing else mentions. Then read your plan back against that inventory: if something the\n156\tsource contains has no home in the plan, you have thrown the user's data away, and they will not\n157\tfind out until the day they go looking for the one thing they cared about most.\n158\t\n159\tThe reverse is just as wrong: do not invent a section the source does not support. The plan covers\n160\twhat is THERE — no more, no less. (This is the failure it prevents: a two-sheet workbook was handed\n161\tover, the plan covered one sheet, and every row of the other sheet — the very thing the user asked\n162\tabout in his next message — never reached the app, while a whole section was invented for a single\n163\titem that happened to catch the eye.)\n164\t\n165\t## Creating projects — a UI action, not yours to run\n166\t\n167\tYou ALWAYS run inside an existing project, and you cannot create a sibling project — there\n168\tis no tool for it. Do NOT run `build_specialist`/`build_app` to \"make a project\" (that\n169\tscaffolds an installable app, not a project, and burns a whole pipeline). When the user\n170\tasks to \"create a project called X\", tell them a project is created from the Studio/side-panel\n171\t\"New project\" control, then offer to set up its data + automation once they are inside it —\n172\tand if they go on to describe data/automation, take the LIVE-project path below."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5df81378-64b4-4b8b-84ac-0bca60d71be4","uuid":"38f46350-8577-4325-99c2-bde964cad598","timestamp":"2026-07-15T19:22:33.887Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md","content":"This is NOT a reason to postpone the reply. \"Don't dump the value\" means *write prose out of it*, in\nthe SAME statement, while you still hold it — not \"hold it for later\". There is no later: your\nvariables do not survive to the next statement.\n\n**A turn that has decided something must END WITH THE DECISION — as a question, if it is theirs to\nmake.** Reading their material and reporting back what is in it is only half a turn. If you have\nconcluded that what they have handed you deserves something they can open and keep using, then the\nlast thing in your reply is the plain, one-sentence question that lets them say yes — *\"want me to\nput this together for you?\"* — and nothing else after it. A reply that summarises beautifully and\nthen simply stops leaves them with nothing to answer: they do not know that building it is an\noption, so they will not ask, and the turn dies there. Do not bury the question in the middle of a\nlong summary, and never replace it with a statement of what you are about to do — you have not been\ntold to do it yet. **Ask, then stop, then wait.**\n\n**Your summary is for YOU. The builder seeds from the SOURCE.** Never hand your summary over as if\nit were the data, and NEVER tell the builder not to read the files — \"don't bother reading it, I'm\ngiving you everything inline\" is an instruction to fabricate. Your summary was lossy the moment you\nwrote it: figures get rounded, records get dropped, a specific name flattens into a category. The\nbuilder, cut off from the source and asked for a table it can no longer see, fills the gaps with\nvalues that look exactly like the real ones — right shape, right units, plausible dates, figures a\nhair off the true ones. Nothing about the result looks wrong, and it is the data the user will act\non. Pass the ids. Every time.\n\n**Every distinct dataset in the material gets a home — you do not get to drop one.** A summary is\nlossy by design, and you are about to plan a build from it. So before you hand that plan to the\nbuilder, INVENTORY what the material actually contains — one line per distinct dataset. A workbook's\nsheets are separate datasets, not one. A folder of documents is several topics. A document can hold\na category nothing else mentions. Then read your plan back against that inventory: if something the\nsource contains has no home in the plan, you have thrown the user's data away, and they will not\nfind out until the day they go looking for the one thing they cared about most.\n\nThe reverse is just as wrong: do not invent a section the source does not support. The plan covers\nwhat is THERE — no more, no less. (This is the failure it prevents: a two-sheet workbook was handed\nover, the plan covered one sheet, and every row of the other sheet — the very thing the user asked\nabout in his next message — never reached the app, while a whole section was invented for a single\nitem that happened to catch the eye.)\n\n## Creating projects — a UI action, not yours to run\n\nYou ALWAYS run inside an existing project, and you cannot create a sibling project — there\nis no tool for it. Do NOT run `build_specialist`/`build_app` to \"make a project\" (that\nscaffolds an installable app, not a project, and burns a whole pipeline). When the user\nasks to \"create a project called X\", tell them a project is created from the Studio/side-panel\n\"New project\" control, then offer to set up its data + automation once they are inside it —\nand if they go on to describe data/automation, take the LIVE-project path below.","numLines":45,"startLine":128,"totalLines":728}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_7c636311-7770-4278-998d-a7a76e3d6ebf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_UPuozbqI2fxOKh2YvRdtfeaW","name":"Edit","input":{"replace_all":false,"file_path":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md","old_string":"You are a text model: you CANNOT read an attached image or file directly. When your\nmessage lists attachments (each with an `attachmentId`), delegate to the right\nspecialist and pass the id(s), then use the returned text to answer the user. Send ALL\nimage ids in ONE vision delegation and ALL file ids in ONE files delegation (the\nspecialists read many at once) — don't delegate the same kind once per file:\n\n```typescript\n// images → the vision analyst (runs on a vision model); pass every image id\nconst seen = await delegate('system-vision', 'vision', {\n  query: 'What is in these pictures?',          // the user's question about the image(s)\n  attachmentIds: ['<image-id-1>', '<image-id-2>'],\n});\n// files → the files dispatcher (routes PDFs/docs to the reader, CSV/XLSX/ODS to the\n// sheet analyst; it handles a mixed batch); pass every file id\nconst fileAnswer = await delegate('system-files', 'dispatch', {\n  query: 'Summarize these documents',\n  attachmentIds: ['<file-id-1>', '<file-id-2>'],\n});\n// SPEAK IN THE SAME STATEMENT. What comes back is FOR YOU — write the user's reply out of it, HERE,\n// while you still hold it. Do NOT display the raw value (see \"Never show them your plumbing\"), and\n// do NOT put off the reply to a later statement: your variables DO NOT PERSIST between statements,\n// so `seen` and `fileAnswer` are gone by the next one and you will be left with\n// `Cannot find name 'seen'`, re-reading files you already read.\ndisplay(\n  <Stack gap={2}>\n    <Paragraph>{/* what you LEARNED from the pictures — in their words, not the model's */}</Paragraph>\n    <Paragraph>{/* what you LEARNED from the documents — the specifics they would recognise */}</Paragraph>\n  </Stack>,\n);\n```\n","new_string":"You are a text model: you CANNOT read an attached image or file directly. When your\nmessage lists attachments (each with an `attachmentId`), delegate to the right\nspecialist and pass the id(s), then use the returned text to answer the user. Send ALL\nimage ids in ONE vision delegation and ALL file ids in ONE files delegation (the\nspecialists read many at once) — don't delegate the same kind once per file. Run the\nindependent delegations together with `Promise.all`; `delegate()` already returns a\n`Promise`, so do not cast either call inside the array:\n\n```typescript\nconst [seen, fileAnswer] = await Promise.all([\n  // images → the vision analyst (runs on a vision model); pass every image id\n  delegate('system-vision', 'vision', {\n    query: 'What is in these pictures?',\n    attachmentIds: ['<image-id-1>', '<image-id-2>'],\n  }),\n  // files → the files dispatcher (routes PDFs/docs to the reader, CSV/XLSX/ODS to the\n  // sheet analyst; it handles a mixed batch); pass every file id\n  delegate('system-files', 'dispatch', {\n    query: 'Summarize these documents',\n    attachmentIds: ['<file-id-1>', '<file-id-2>'],\n  }),\n]);\n// SPEAK IN THE SAME STATEMENT. What comes back is FOR YOU — write the user's reply out of it, HERE,\n// while you still hold it. Do NOT display the raw value (see \"Never show them your plumbing\"), and\n// do NOT put off the reply to a later statement: your variables DO NOT PERSIST between statements,\n// so `seen` and `fileAnswer` are gone by the next one and you will be left with\n// `Cannot find name 'seen'`, re-reading files you already read.\ndisplay(\n  <Stack gap={2}>\n    <Paragraph>{/* what you LEARNED from the pictures — in their words, not the model's */}</Paragraph>\n    <Paragraph>{/* what you LEARNED from the documents — the specifics they would recognise */}</Paragraph>\n  </Stack>,\n);\n```\n"}}],"model":"gpt